metadata.name: Urban Flora #172
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.description:
Tribute to the Swiss artist Emma Kunz (1892-1963). She rejected the idea of art versus non-art, and instead expanded her definition to include research, medicine, and nature, as well as the supernatural, magical, and visionary. Don't stop discovering her art!

This piece is inspired by her uncompromising handling of geometry and the colorful, freehand pictorial finish of her work, a sensibility with which I connect very deeply.

"KUNZ'S DREAM" is a generative piece of software coded using p5js by a biological intelligence.

metadata.name: Glyphs #3
metadata.description:
Glyphs attempts to expand upon the seemingly random, yet beautiful forms found in the world around us. They capture the structured randomness in everyday life. 

Inspired by the handwritten form and the spatial complexities of figure ground maps within the urban context.

Glyphs are randomly produced within a set of rules, some more complex than others.

There are 11 color palette options, each containing a number of specific color options.  

Two main graphics options require different compute times. Faded outputs will take longer to render than others. For this reason I have required a 60s view capture to ensure everyone gets a thumbnail regardless of the features.

‚ÄúS‚Äù - save image as .JPG

Glyphs | cmplx 2022 | JPG | 2500x2500

metadata.name: Flux #11
metadata.description:
Isn't it beautiful to know that everything is constantly changing? From our bodies, to the objects around us, nature, planets and everything else in our universe.

The only thing that keeps us from accepting this constant state of flux is our own minds. It likes certainty, it fears change, it wants everything to stay as it is.

This art piece is a representation of that constant imperfect state of change. From calm and focused movements to more erratic, aggressive versions of the same piece.

Written in glsl to leverage the power of the gpu, projected onto an orthographic quad.

one - Mentions to @polyclickkkkk (twitter) or @polyclick (ig) will be reposted.
two - 25% will be donated to thebookofshaders.com

"The Only Constant in Life Is Change." - Heraclitus.

metadata.name: Divisio(X) #248
metadata.description:
On a dynamic grid (2x2, 3x3, 4x4, 5x5 or 6x6), each cell is filled with one shape (out of 6). For each shape, a rotation (0¬∞, 90¬∞, 180¬∞, 270¬∞) and a stroke weight (from 5 to 100) are applied. A color palette (out of 6) and a number of layers (1 to 3) are applied to the canvas.

The background under the shape can be filled by cells, rows or columns. At times, a thick grid may also be visible.	

Generative abstract compositions. Coded in January 2022.

metadata.name: spaceplant #124
metadata.description:
Natural processes are computational at their very core, and like atoms, gravity, electricity, the sun, the moon, and the big bang, computation tells part of our cosmological story.

The "spaceplant" series expresses this "computational beauty of nature" (a phrase borrowed from Gary William Flake's book of that title) through a lo-fi simulated garden. This garden has been grown by collecting, curating and nurturing algorithmic specimens that inhabit a space both cellular and planetary. A symphony of particle forces orchestrates the form and interaction of the simulation, tuned to cosmological constants by the artist.

49 kB of compiled JavaScript. Code written 100% from scratch with no dependencies. Mouse interactive.

metadata.name: Torsion #237
metadata.description:
This project aims to explore the possibilities offered by the implementation of a simulation of slit-scanning or rolling-shutter.
A line runs through a 3D animation and freezes the pixels at its level. This results in a distortion effect giving the initial objects twisted and strange shapes.

Artist: Estienne
License: NFT 2.0
Feb. 2022

metadata.name: Complex World #12
metadata.description:
"Complex World" is a genesis collection on fx(hash).
In this collection, I present to you a series of generative voxel art consisting of 36 unique pieces. These artworks are created using JSplacement, a powerful tool that generates pseudo-random 8K displacement maps.
The surfaces produced by JSplacement form the basis of these generative voxel art pieces.
The random details and vibrant colors come together to create a captivating 3D space that invites you to imagine the possibilities of a connected future,
where technology and creativity intertwine to shape new realities.

metadata.name: stacks #92
metadata.description:
An exploration of vernacular architectural forms and combinatorial logics. If the roof form is typically what gives a building its character (i.e., its primary reading in a public-facing elevation), we can play with those proportions to achieve a particular reading. Square proportions become domestic, while shallower gables suggest more industrial typologies, narrower ones may even feel religious. Mixing a variety of proportions together allow for a proto-urban cacophony of elevational readings. These generative compositions play with both existing perceptions of the built environment as well as imaginary potentials of future architectures to come.

As impossible as these compositions may seem, they are fully realized as 3D forms, extruded at various lengths, all connected to a fictional ‚Äúground‚Äù. They are rendered using an elevation oblique projection, a form of parallel projection that visually distorts the geometry to show accurate depth and a true frontal elevation.

Press 's' in live mode to save a PNG.

metadata.name: INSTRUCTURES #179
metadata.description:
Instructures explores the endless and diverse outcomes when a minimal and straightforward set of instructions are followed to build structures out of cubes. Between 4 and 8 instructions are selected and used to generate a unique structure for each edition. The available instructions are ‚Äústack‚Äù, ‚Äúpile‚Äù, ‚Äúplane‚Äù and ‚Äúsculpt‚Äù. As a last step, flat and/or rounded corner details are optionally added to each structure.

Each artwork includes the set of instructions that were followed to build the structure. These instructions can be followed to build new structures using other methods in addition to programming, e.g. sculpting, printing, drawing, painting etc., and I plan on using this body of work to do exactly that. This project is, in fact, the result of an algorithm initially developed to generate interesting compositions and structures out of cubes to be used as points of departure for drawings, prints and paintings.

Even though the algorithm is focused on generating unique structures, the additional variations in scale, composition, colour, viewing angle and drawing style create an even wider array of generative outcomes. Some outputs are recognisable as three-dimensional orthographic drawings while others are more abstract. Instructures attempts to strike a balance between traditional art and the more technical nature of computer and blockchain art by blending visual cues from both disciplines. My hope is that the works can be appreciated by audiences from both of these worlds.

‚ÄúThe idea becomes a machine that makes the art.‚Äù ‚Äî Sol Lewitt

metadata.name: Gradient Rect #156
metadata.description:
Gradient Rect generates an image with many rectangular color gradients. Depending on the number and size of the rectangles generated, there may be collisions and overlap that bring the gradient rectangles together as part of a larger picture. In cases of limited or no overlap, the sparsity may highlight the composition created by filled and empty space. With several colorways and randomization of each feature, there are many possibilities that will allow for each image to be unique.

Gradient Rect was based on an algorithm originally developed to serve as a background image that transitions from one extreme color to another (#ff0000, #00ff00, #0000ff, #ffff00, #00ffff, or #ff00ff). Expanding on that, the algorithm used in Gradient Rect is capable of fading from any color in the RGB spectrum to any other color in the RGB spectrum and applies this in a loop at randomly chosen locations on the canvas. While the colors may be completely random, they can also be chosen from a palette, or a mixture of the two.
